msContents.summary: Compostite manuscript written in at least three hands and on more than one type of paper containing eight treatises on astronomy and arithmetic with an introduction; diagrams within and between the works. Some of the works are dedicated to Muḥammad Valī Mīrzā, the third son of Fatḥ ʻAlī Shāh Qajar (see for example, f. 171v, 279r).

supportDesc.extent: 278 leaves : 200 x 140 mm, bound to 200 x 140 mm

layoutDesc.layout: Various layouts, but chiefly written 14-17 long lines.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Chiefly written in nastaʻlīq in black ink; pointed; some marginalia in shikastah and some quotations in naskh.

decoDesc.decoNote: Rubrications chiefly in red with a few in brown; numerous diagrams in red, black, and brown; some tables in red and black.

binding.p: Bound in reddish leather over pasteboard; gold tooled frame; black doublure.

origin.p: Works 3, 5, 6 dated 1241 A.H. (f. 46v, 78v, 97r); works 8 and 9 dated 1245 A.H. (f. 171r); work 10 is dated 983 A.H. (255r); work 11 is undated.

history.provenance: Gift of Sam Schaefler (library bookplate inside front cover).
